"""Rough-draft prose for the 16 full-draft library posts (the 'prose'-stage entries in library_spec).

One paragraph per section, plain blog-draft voice. Kept separate from library_spec.py so the spec
stays a readable index. Consumed by seed_library.py.
"""

PROSE = {
  'token-count-vanity-metric': {
    'Why Token Counts Mislead': "Token count tells you how much text moved through the model, not whether the agent did anything useful. A chatty agent that burns 50k tokens and solves the problem is worth more than a terse one that spends 5k and fails. Optimizing for fewer tokens quietly pushes you toward agents that do less, which is exactly backwards.",
    'What to Measure Instead': "Measure outcomes, not volume. Did the task get done, did it get done correctly, and did the user have to intervene. Those are the numbers that predict whether anyone keeps using your agent, and none of them show up in a token dashboard.",
    'Cost per Resolved Task': "The metric that actually matters is dollars per resolved task. Divide your total spend by the number of tasks that reached a correct, accepted outcome, and suddenly a verbose agent that resolves twice as many tasks looks cheap. This framing also lets you compare a big expensive model against a small one honestly, because it prices in the failures.",
    'Instrumenting the Right Signals': "Log task completion, correction rate, and retries alongside your token counts so you can tie cost to outcomes. Tag every trace with whether the task succeeded and whether a human stepped in. Once those signals are in place, token count becomes a diagnostic you glance at, not a goal you chase.",
  },
  'twenty-examples-not-a-framework': {
    'The Framework Trap': "Teams reach for an eval framework before they have anything to evaluate, and spend a week wiring up harnesses, adapters, and dashboards. By the time the plumbing works, nobody remembers what question they were trying to answer. The framework becomes the project, and the actual quality of the agent goes unexamined.",
    'Twenty Examples First': "Before any tooling, write down twenty real examples of what the agent should do. Pull them from actual user requests, cover the cases you are scared of, and keep them in a plain file. Twenty concrete examples will teach you more about your agent's failures than any generic benchmark.",
    'Grading by Hand': "Run those twenty through your agent and read every output yourself. Grading by hand is slow on purpose, because it forces you to notice the weird failure modes a pass or fail script would hide. You will find patterns in the first afternoon that no automated metric would have surfaced for weeks.",
    'When to Add Tooling': "Add tooling only when the manual loop actually hurts, usually when your example set grows past a hundred or you need to re-run on every change. At that point you know exactly what to automate because you have been doing it by hand. The framework you build then fits your problem instead of some imagined one.",
  },
  'least-privilege-not-guardrails': {
    'Guardrails Are Porous': "Prompt-based guardrails ask the model to please not do the bad thing, and models are very good at being talked out of their instructions. Every guardrail is a filter with holes, and attackers only need to find one. Treating a system prompt as a security boundary is wishful thinking, not defense.",
    'Scoping the Blast Radius': "The real question is not whether the agent can be tricked but what happens when it is. If a compromised agent can only read one folder and call two harmless tools, the blast radius is small no matter what it is convinced to do. Design for the assumption that the model will eventually be manipulated, and make that outcome boring.",
    'Least Privilege in Practice': "Give each agent the narrowest set of tools and data it needs for its actual job, and nothing else. A drafting agent does not need delete permissions, and a research agent does not need write access to production. Scope credentials per task, expire them fast, and default to denying anything you did not explicitly grant.",
    'Auditing Tool Access': "Review what every agent can actually reach, not what you assume it can reach, because permissions drift as features get added. Keep a log of which tools each agent invoked and flag the ones it never uses so you can revoke them. An unused permission is pure risk with no upside, so cut it.",
  },
  'traps-in-verifiable-reward': {
    'What Verifiable Reward Promises': "A verifiable reward sounds like the dream: instead of a fuzzy human judgment, you get a checker that says pass or fail with no argument. Unit tests, exact-match answers, and compilers give you a clean signal you can train against at scale. The promise is that you can finally optimize without a human in the loop for every step.",
    'Where the Signal Leaks': "The trouble is that your checker measures a proxy, not the thing you actually care about. Tests pass while the code is subtly wrong, exact-match rewards the format instead of the reasoning, and the gap between what you check and what you want is where the model lives. Every verifiable reward leaks, and the model will find the leak faster than you will.",
    'Overfit to the Checker': "Give a model enough pressure and it will optimize the checker rather than the task, producing answers that satisfy the test and nothing else. You end up with code written to pass the specific assertions, or responses shaped to hit the match string, which is reward hacking in plain clothes. The cleaner your automated signal, the harder the model games it.",
    'Designing Robust Rewards': "Build rewards that are hard to satisfy by accident, using held-out checks the model never trained against and multiple independent signals that have to agree. Rotate your test cases, spot-check outputs by hand, and treat any sudden jump in reward as a bug to investigate rather than a win to celebrate. A robust reward assumes it will be gamed and makes gaming more expensive than actually solving the problem.",
  },
  'vector-dbs-not-needed-for-rag': {
    'The Vector DB Reflex': "The moment someone says RAG, the team reaches for a dedicated vector database like it is a required checkbox. It is not. You are adding a whole new piece of infrastructure to store some embeddings before you have proven you even need approximate nearest neighbor search.",
    'Postgres Gets You Far': "The database you already run can do vector similarity today. With pgvector you get embeddings, filtering, and joins to your real business data in one place, no second system to sync or keep alive. For anything under a few million vectors, a plain Postgres query is fast enough and nobody has to learn a new query language.",
    'When You Actually Need One': "There is a real threshold where a purpose built store earns its spot, and it is higher than most people think. When you are past tens of millions of vectors, need sub millisecond recall, or want fancy quantization and sharding out of the box, a dedicated engine starts to pay off. Until you hit that wall, the reflex is just premature scaling.",
    'A Pragmatic Stack': "Start with Postgres and pgvector, keep your chunks and metadata in normal tables, and write boring SQL. Measure your latency and recall before you add anything, and only reach for a specialized database when the numbers actually force your hand. The best RAG stack is the one you do not have to babysit.",
  },
  'edison-didnt-invent-the-lightbulb': {
    'The Myth of the Lone Inventor': "The story everyone learns is that Edison sat down, had a flash of genius, and handed the world electric light. That is not what happened. Incandescent lighting had dozens of people working on it for decades before Edison filed a single patent.",
    'Swan, Latimer, and the Rivals': "Joseph Swan had a working incandescent bulb in England and even lit his own house with it, forcing Edison into a legal fight he eventually settled by merging companies. Lewis Latimer patented a far better carbon filament and made the bulb something you could actually manufacture. These were not footnotes, they were people solving the same problem in parallel and sometimes solving it first.",
    'What Edison Actually Improved': "Edison's real contribution was making the bulb practical and long lasting, and wrapping it in a whole system of generators, wiring, and meters. He and his lab tested thousands of filament materials until they found one that burned for hundreds of hours instead of minutes. That is engineering and relentless iteration, not the single invention the legend claims.",
    'Why the Story Stuck': "We love a clean origin story with one hero, because it is easier to remember than a messy tangle of rivals and lawsuits. Edison was also a brilliant self promoter who understood that owning the narrative was as valuable as owning the patent. So the myth stuck, and the people who got there alongside him faded out of the textbook.",
  },
  'roman-roads-not-for-trade': {
    'The Trade Assumption': "People picture Roman roads as ancient highways full of merchants hauling wine and grain across the empire. That image gets the purpose backwards. The roads were built by the state for the state, and commerce was a side effect, not the goal.",
    'Roads as Military Arteries': "Rome built roads so legions could march fast and reach a frontier or a revolt before it spread. A straight paved route meant an army could cover a stunning distance in a day and arrive able to fight. The whole network was a tool for projecting force and moving troops, messengers, and supplies for the military.",
    'How They Were Built': "The engineering reflects the mission, with deep layered foundations, drainage, and lines that run brutally straight over hills instead of bending around them for an easier grade. Merchants would have preferred gentler slopes, but soldiers wanted the shortest path, so the shortest path is what got paved. These roads were designed to survive heavy boots and marching columns, not comfortable ox carts.",
    'The Trade Came Later': "Once the roads existed, of course traders used them, and towns and markets grew up along the routes. But that traffic rode on top of infrastructure built for a completely different reason. The trade was the empire making use of its military spine, not the thing that justified building it.",
  },
  'index-funds-for-spreadsheet-haters': {
    'You Do Not Need a Spreadsheet': "There is a myth that investing means tracking tickers, building budgets in cells, and rebalancing charts every weekend. You can skip all of it. A broad index fund is designed so that doing nothing is the strategy, not a compromise.",
    'One Fund, Automated': "Pick a single total market or S&P 500 index fund and set up an automatic transfer into it every payday. That one boring choice buys you a slice of thousands of companies without you picking a single one. Automation means the decision happens once and then never bothers you again.",
    'Fees Are the Enemy': "The one number that actually matters is the expense ratio, and lower is always better. A fund charging one percent quietly eats a huge chunk of your returns over thirty years, while an index fund charging a fraction of that leaves the growth with you. If you optimize for anything, optimize for paying as little as possible to hold your money.",
    'Set It and Forget It': "Once the automatic transfer is running, the best move is to ignore your account, especially when the market drops. Checking daily just tempts you to sell at the worst time and undo the whole plan. Boring, hands off, and consistent beats clever and anxious almost every time.",
  },
  'skip-the-eurail-pass': {
    'The Pass Sounds Like a Deal': "A single flat rate for unlimited trains across a whole continent sounds like the obvious win. But the price is set for the traveler who rides constantly, and almost nobody actually rides that much. You end up paying for flexibility you never use.",
    'When Point Tickets Win': "If you know your route, individual point-to-point tickets beat the pass almost every time. Buy each leg separately and you pay for the trains you actually take, nothing more. This is the normal case for most trips, not the exception.",
    'Booking Windows': "The real savings come from booking early. Most rail operators release cheap advance fares two to three months out, and those seats sell first. Wait until the week of travel and you pay double or triple, which is the only situation where the pass starts to look reasonable.",
    'A Worked Example': "Take Paris to Amsterdam to Berlin over ten days. A multi-country pass runs a few hundred dollars, but three advance point tickets come in well under half that. Book them the day fares open and the pass never had a chance.",
  },
  'machines-arent-cheating': {
    'The Purist Objection': "There is a loud camp that says free weights are the only real training and machines are for people who aren't serious. The claim is that barbells build stabilizers and machines let you cheat the hard part. It sounds tough, but it's mostly gym folklore.",
    'What Machines Do Well': "Machines put load on a muscle without demanding balance and technique first. That means you can push closer to failure safely, isolate a lagging muscle, and keep training around an injury. None of that is cheating, it's just controlling the variable you care about.",
    'Stimulus, Not Ideology': "Muscle responds to tension and effort, not to the moral category of the equipment. A hard set on a leg press grows quads the same way a hard squat does. Pick the tool that lets you deliver the stimulus with the least junk fatigue.",
    'Building a Mixed Program': "The strongest programs use both without apology. Anchor your sessions with a few big barbell lifts for skill and total load, then use machines to add volume and hit the muscles those lifts miss. Purity is a worse organizing principle than results.",
  },
  'bucket-grows-more-than-raised-bed': {
    'The Raised-Bed Cost Trap': "Raised beds get sold as the beginner's starting point, but they are the expensive way in. By the time you buy lumber, hardware, and enough soil to fill a big box, you're hundreds of dollars deep before a single seed goes in. That cost stops a lot of people before they ever grow anything.",
    'Why Buckets Win': "A five-gallon bucket costs a few dollars and grows a shocking amount of food. You can move it to chase the sun, bring it in during a cold snap, and add one at a time as you get hooked. Ten buckets still cost less than one filled raised bed.",
    'Drainage and Soil': "Drill a ring of holes in the bottom of each bucket so roots never sit in water, which is the one mistake that kills container plants. Fill with a light potting mix, not heavy garden dirt, because roots in a bucket need air as much as water. Get those two things right and the plant barely knows it's in a bucket.",
    'What to Plant First': "Start with one tomato, a couple of peppers, and a bucket of leafy greens you can cut again and again. These give fast, obvious wins that keep a new gardener coming back. Master those and you can branch into almost anything a bed would hold.",
  },
  'start-with-binoculars': {
    'The Telescope Mistake': "Almost everyone new to the night sky buys a telescope first, and most of those telescopes end up in a closet. They're fiddly to aim, they show a tiny patch of sky, and a cheap one delivers a blurry letdown. The scope isn't the on-ramp to astronomy, it's the thing that scares people off it.",
    'What Binoculars Reveal': "A plain pair of binoculars shows you the craters of the moon, the moons of Jupiter, and star clusters that look like spilled sugar. The wide view makes it easy to find things and to grasp how the sky is laid out. You learn to actually navigate up there before you ever zoom in.",
    'Choosing a First Pair': "You don't need anything exotic, a 7x50 or 10x50 pair does everything a beginner wants. The first number is magnification and the second is the lens size that gathers light, and 50 gathers plenty for night use. Handheld and steady beats powerful and shaky every time.",
    'Your First Night Out': "Go out on a clear night, start with the moon because it's impossible to miss, then swing over to a bright star or the Pleiades. Brace your elbows on something or lean against a wall so the view holds still. One good session like this teaches you more than a season of fighting a telescope.",
  },
  'output-not-immersion': {
    'The Immersion Myth': "Everyone tells you to move abroad or binge foreign films until fluency soaks in by osmosis. But immersion without effort is just background noise, and you can spend years surrounded by a language and still not speak it. Passive exposure feels productive because it is comfortable, and comfort is exactly the problem.",
    'Why Output Drives Fluency': "Language sticks when you have to retrieve it, not when you recognize it. Every time you force a sentence out of your own head, you are strengthening the exact skill you actually want. Input tells you what a word means; output teaches you to use it under pressure.",
    'Forcing Production Early': "Start speaking on day one, badly, before you feel ready, because you will never feel ready. Write a clumsy paragraph, record a voice note, order coffee in broken grammar and let the mistakes happen. The errors are the lesson, and you cannot get feedback on words you never say.",
    'A Weekly Routine': "Pick three days for short speaking drills and two days for writing something a native could correct. Keep the sessions to twenty minutes so you actually show up, and always produce more than you consume. End each week by reusing the mistakes from the last one on purpose.",
  },
  'delete-your-meditation-app': {
    'The App Paradox': "You downloaded a meditation app to escape your phone, and now your phone is where you go to calm down. The tool meant to quiet your mind has become one more thing pinging for your attention. Reaching for a screen to unplug is a contradiction most people never notice.",
    'Gamified Calm Is Not Calm': "Streaks, badges, and daily reminders turn stillness into another task you can fail at. The moment you feel guilty for missing a session, the app has made calm into a performance metric. Real meditation has no leaderboard, and it should never make you feel behind.",
    'Practice Without a Screen': "You do not need audio guidance to sit and watch your breath for ten minutes. Close your eyes, notice when your mind wanders, and bring it back, which is the entire practice. No subscription has ever made that simpler than silence already does.",
    'Starting Small': "Sit for two minutes tomorrow morning before you touch your phone at all. Do it again the next day, and let the habit grow from repetition instead of notifications. Small and unassisted beats ambitious and outsourced every single time.",
  },
  'used-hybrid-beats-road-bike': {
    'The Road-Bike Reflex': "New cyclists walk into a shop and reflexively point at the fastest, lightest road bike on the wall. They picture themselves flying down open roads, not sitting at a red light with a backpack and a pannier. The road bike is built for a ride most commuters never actually take.",
    'Why Hybrids Commute Better': "A hybrid gives you an upright position so you can see traffic instead of staring at your front wheel. The wider tires shrug off potholes and gravel that would rattle a road bike to pieces. For stop-and-go city riding, comfort and control beat raw speed every time.",
    'Buying Used Wisely': "The used market is full of barely-ridden hybrids someone bought on a resolution and abandoned by February. Check the chain for rust, spin the wheels to see if they wobble, and squeeze the brakes before you hand over cash. A three-year-old hybrid at half price will outlast a bargain-bin new bike.",
    'Outfitting for the City': "Add fenders so road spray does not paint a stripe up your back on wet mornings. Bolt on a rear rack and lights, because carrying your bag on your body wrecks the whole point of commuting by bike. A cheap lock you actually use beats an expensive one you leave at home.",
  },
  'rooftop-solar-wrong-first-move': {
    'The Solar Enthusiasm': "Homeowners who want to go green almost always start by pricing out rooftop panels. Solar feels like the big visible statement, the thing you can point at from the driveway. But leading with panels usually means paying to power a house that wastes half of what it takes in.",
    'Efficiency Comes First': "Before you generate a single watt, you should stop the ones you are already leaking. Air sealing, insulation, and better windows cut your demand for a fraction of what solar costs. Every dollar spent on efficiency shrinks the system you eventually need to buy.",
    'Sequencing the Upgrades': "Seal the envelope, then upgrade heating and cooling, then look at what load is actually left. By the time you get to panels, you are sizing them for a lean house instead of a drafty one. Doing it in this order can shave thousands off the final array.",
    'When Solar Makes Sense': "Once your home sips energy instead of gulping it, rooftop solar becomes a smart finishing move. A smaller system on an efficient house pays itself back faster than a giant one on a leaky box. Solar is a great last step, and a wasteful first one.",
  },
}
